@jvanverth thank you for update, we all waiting for solution, since currently Flutter is not actually usable on iOS. Flutter 1.12.13-x still in production because of the iOS Metal janks. 

But could you please clarify solution planned? Is that "something" we have to precache and include to the app build?  
What about if some deep-in-app animation cannot be easily precached, it will be janky as any animation right now?

@meowofficial `firebase_crashlytics` has false Dart sdk version limit, you can easily fork it, fix Dard sdk version and use on old Flutter.

> @meowofficial `firebase_crashlytics` has false Dart sdk version limit, you can easily fork it, fix Dard sdk version and use on old Flutter.

@totalerex Unfortunately, there are way more packages that have to be downgraded (some of them can be with important bug fixes).  Additionally, there were some fixes especially for iOS 14, so flutter 1.12.13-x doesn't support them.

It is really really bad that the flutter team busy with the implementation of any other features while there is such an obvious problem with performance.

@alexandrius If they've done that the app would be too big.

> Why not just compile or warm up all possible shaders?
If there are only a limited number of possible shaders, then Flutter could do a warm-up and compile all of them before-hand to avoid such jank. However, for the best overall performance, the Skia GPU backend used by Flutter can dynamically generate shaders based on a lot of parameters at runtime (for example, draws, device models, and driver versions). Due to all possible combinations of those parameters, the number of possible shaders is exponential. In short, Flutter uses programs (app, Flutter, and Skia code) to generate some other programs (shaders). The number of possible shader programs that Flutter can generate is simply too large.

@dnfield , I think you are not too precise in suggestions:
1. Flutter 1.12.13 (OpenGL) is running on iOS smoothly until now. OpenGL was deprecated by Apple long time ago and nothing was preventing Google-Flutter team to postpone Metal-Flutter a little big more to time janks are resolved.
2. No excuses for not resolving janks issues since 1.17 was releases. Flutter just not usable on iOS now.
3. It is funny that you think we can find someone experienced in C++ (f.e. switched from C++ to Flutter) can help us with Skia :) . But I personaly think that you personally could help investigate why janks are much heavier in case using flutter_svg (published by you, right?), may be there is something special we could find workaround, my be there is nothing to do with shaders, may be there is bug in something related to drawPath or what ever used a lot in flutter_svg?    

Our app is running on Flutter 1.12.13 and we have almost 40% dependencies forked in order to support old flutter and have dependencies updated. You can imagine how much work we do, all because our QA, and developers actually too, prefer to be fired than let users see such janks/lags. Don't Flutter team has manual testers? Than it is big gap :)  

@csells @filiph, may be I'm too naive to hope you see this, but I and all people in trouble kindly ask you to investigate not this particular issue but the general problem we have with janks/lags on iOS after Flutter switched to Metal. This problem has big history and many bugs closed by formal reasons.
